And this is that which St. Chrysostom, Oecumenius, Theodoret, Theophylact, and many other ancient Writers have very well observed. For St. Chrysostom in his Comment upon this very Text sayes, that in this childhood, this nonage of the Church,
〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉 , That nothing was done as Mans Wisdome did direct;
〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉 , but by the direction of Gods Spirit: whose business 'twas not onely 〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉 , to foretell things to come;
〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉 , but to reveal things present too, especially in the choice of fit Rulers in the Church. Clemens Romanus speaking of those Rulers sayes, That the first Bishops which were made were made by the Apostles, 〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉 , having tryed them by the Spirit. Oecumenius also speaks as if the other held his pen, and sayes almost in the same form of words, 〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉 , The first Bishops were made Bishops by the appointment of Gods Spirit. Thus St. Paul and Barnabas were of Preachers made Apostles, Act. 13. 2. thus Titus was made Metropolitane of Creet, Tit. 1. 5. and thus
Timothy in this Text was made the first Ephesian Bishop,
〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉 , by the Spirit of God designing of him by the Prophets.
